# An explicit `string` annotation on a string-literal binding widens it:
# checking the annotation against the literal body must not warn, since
# LiteralString <: String (eu-19do / A4). The widened value then passes a
# string-typed function without warning...
` { type: "string" }
x: "hello"

` { type: "string → number" }
length: str.len

ok: length(x)

# ...but widening to `string` does not make the value usable as a number —
# passing it to a number-typed function still warns. This is the
# observable half of the test: without it, an exit-0 check alone could not
# distinguish "the checker verified widening" from "the checker silently
# skipped the annotation" (eu-3621 — this fixture originally used
# unsupported inline ascription syntax `expr : "type"`, which never parsed,
# so `eu check --strict` exited 0 for the wrong reason: a parse error it
# failed to propagate, not a passing check).
` { type: "number → number" }
double: (_ * 2)

bad: double(x)
